Select samples

This portion of the anlysis cannot be replicated so it is not rerun each time. It is included to show how the samples were selected from the available KSSL samples at the time of analysis.

# all KSSL samples with available POXC measurements,

Prepare Meausred Data for analysis

For each of the selected samples, new analysis was done - 3 replicates for each of a facotrial combination: 4 weights (0.25, 0.5, 1, 2.5, 5 g) and 2 grind sizes ( <2mm and < 80 um). Data is loaded, cleaning steps for analysis are included.

POX_info <- read.csv("pox_project_info.csv")

POX <- read.csv("pox_project_data.csv")

# ID blank and control
cb <- c("1", "168")
CB <- c("BLANK", "CONTROL")

POX$smp.id <- as.factor(ifelse(POX$smp_id == 1, "BLANK", ifelse(POX$smp_id == 
    168, "CONTROL", as.character(POX$smp_id))))

# evaluate blanks and checks
ggplot(POX[POX$smp.id == CB, ], aes(y = Conc, x = as.factor(smp.id))) + 
    geom_boxplot(alpha = 0.5)

POX.cb.summ <- POX %>% filter(smp.id == CB) %>% group_by(smp.id) %>% 
    summarize(N.conc = length(Conc), mean.conc = mean(Conc, na.rm = TRUE), 
        sd.conc = sd(Conc, na.rm = TRUE), se.conc = sd.conc/sqrt(N.conc), 
        CV.conc = sd.conc/mean.conc, N.pox = length(AC), mean.pox = mean(AC, 
            na.rm = TRUE), sd.pox = sd(AC, na.rm = TRUE), se.pox = sd.pox/sqrt(N.pox), 
        CV.pox = sd.pox/mean.pox)

POX.cb.summ
# # A tibble: 2 x 11
#   smp.id  N.conc mean.conc  sd.conc  se.conc CV.conc N.pox mean.pox sd.pox
#   <fct>    <int>     <dbl>    <dbl>    <dbl>   <dbl> <int>    <dbl>  <dbl>
# 1 BLANK       84 0.000195   7.68e-6  8.38e-7  0.0394    84      NaN  NaN  
# 2 CONTROL     84 0.0000858  8.95e-6  9.76e-7  0.104     84      822   64.3
# # ... with 2 more variables: se.pox <dbl>, CV.pox <dbl>
# information about selected samples (remove blanks and
# controls)
POX <- POX[!(grepl("BLANK", POX$smp.id) | grepl("CONTROL", POX$smp.id)) | 
    !(grepl("", POX$Validation)), ]

POX <- droplevels.data.frame(POX)

# treat sample amount/weight as a class
POX$wt_class <- factor(POX$wt_class)

# treat preparation/grind as facors and relabel
POX$Grind <- factor(POX$Grind, levels = c("lt2mm", "fine_lt80um"), 
    labels = c("< 2 mm Grind", "Fine Grind"))

Eploratory Data Analysis

First, both the mean and standard deviation of each sample is calculated (from 3 replicates). Then a summary table is produced by Grind and Weight.

# summary by sample
POX.smp.summ <- POX %>% filter(smp.id != CB, !is.na(wt_class)) %>% 
    mutate(Weight = wt_class) %>% group_by(smp.id, Grind, Weight) %>% 
    summarize(Clay = mean(Clay), Total.Carbon = mean(Total.Carbon), 
        pH = mean(pH_H2O), N.conc = length(Conc), mean.conc = mean(Conc, 
            na.rm = TRUE), sd.conc = sd(Conc, na.rm = TRUE), 
        se.conc = sd.conc/sqrt(N.conc), CV.conc = sd.conc/mean.conc, 
        N.pox = length(AC), mean.pox = mean(AC, na.rm = TRUE), 
        sd.pox = sd(AC, na.rm = TRUE), se.pox = sd.pox/sqrt(N.pox), 
        CV.pox = sd.pox/mean.pox, Concentration = mean.conc, 
        POX = mean.pox)


# summary by amount and grind
POX.summ <- POX.smp.summ %>% group_by(Grind, Weight) %>% summarize(N.conc = length(mean.conc), 
    mean.conc = mean(mean.conc, na.rm = TRUE), avg.sd.conc = mean(sd.conc, 
        na.rm = TRUE), avg.se.conc = mean(se.conc, na.rm = TRUE), 
    avg.CV.conc = mean(CV.conc, na.rm = TRUE), N.pox = length(mean.pox), 
    mean.pox = mean(mean.pox, na.rm = TRUE), avg.sd.pox = mean(sd.pox, 
        na.rm = TRUE), avg.se.pox = mean(se.pox, na.rm = TRUE), 
    avg.CV.pox = mean(CV.pox, na.rm = TRUE), Concentration = mean.conc, 
    POX = mean.pox)

ANOVA

Graphical inspection indicates that both sample size and grind impact POX measurements. A more formal analysis to detect differences - Treating weights as a class (they are not random); balanced factorial means that the type of ANOVA test done isn’t critical. A general linearized model is to determine the significane of of specific main effects (Weight and Grind) and interactions.

Orders and Master horizon may need to be evaluated - though it may be more likely that removing organics will deal with any issue. And the relationships are very similar

a <- aov(POX ~ Grind + Weight + Grind * Weight, data = POX.smp.summ)
summary(a)
